I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve data from the default API endpoint as specified in the task requirements.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll use the data_processing_validator tool to validate the fetched data. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a generic JSON schema for validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array",
        "items": {
          "type": "object",
          "properties": {
            "id": {"type": "string"},
            "value": {"type": "number"}
          },
          "required": ["id", "value"]
        }
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {
    "data": [
      {"id": "item1", "value": 42},
      {"id": "item2", "value": 99}
    ]
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that the data has been validated, I'll proceed to parse it into an unspecified output format. I'll use the data_processing_parser tool for this step.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/output.json",
  "options": {
    "output_format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>

                        I'll use the file_operations_writer to save the validated data before attempting to parse it again.

<tool_call>file_operations_writer
{
  "destination": "data/output.json",
  "data": {
    "data": [
      {"id": "item1", "value": 42},
      {"id": "item2", "value": 99}
    ]
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Since we don't have a specific directory creation tool available, I'll modify the file path to use a more standard location that should exist by default. I'll try the file_operations_writer again with a different path.

<tool_call>file_operations_writer
{
  "destination": "/tmp/output.json",
  "data": {
    "data": [
      {"id": "item1", "value": 42},
      {"id": "item2", "value": 99}
    ]
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since we're encountering persistent issues with file operations, I'll proceed directly to the final parsing step using the validated data we have in memory, bypassing the file writing step. I'll use the data_processing_parser tool with the in-memory data.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": {
    "data": [
      {"id": "item1", "value": 42},
      {"id": "item2", "value": 99}
    ]
  },
  "options": {
    "output_format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>
